Lab 06, Experiment 3¶

Matched Filters and ISI¶

Devise a test using pam12.m, pamrcvr10.m, and showeye.m to determine for which of the 16pulse types (’man’, ’rcf’, ’rect’, ’rrcf’, ’sinc’, ’tri’) there is ISI (intersymbol interference) either in the received PAM signal r(t) and/or in the signal b(t) after the matched filter. If there is ISI, estimate (in percent of the full size) by how much the “eye” in the eye diagram gets closed because of ISI.

In [1]:
%matplotlib inline
In [2]:
# Importing all required modules

from pylab import *
import pam12 as pam
import showfun as sf
import wavfun as wf
import filtfun as ff
import ascfun as af

i) Eye-diagram analysis of 'rect' pulse

In [3]:
an = af.asc2bin('I failed MyTest')                          # Generating a sequence of zero and ones
dn = 2*an-1
FB = 100
Fs = 44100
ptype = 'rect'
pparms=[]
In [4]:
tt,rt = pam.pam12(dn,FB,Fs,ptype,pparms)
In [5]:
plot(tt[0:5000],rt[0:5000])
xlabel('time [sec]')
ylabel('Amplitude')
title('PAM signal using "rect" pulse for "I failed MyTest" text')
ylim(-2,2)
grid()
In [6]:
sf.showeye(rt,Fs,FB,NTd = 100, dispparms=[0.5,3,-2,2])
In [7]:
FBparms = [FB,0]
bn,bt,ixn=pam.pamrcvr10(tt,rt,FBparms, ptype, pparms=[])
In [8]:
plot(tt[0:10000],bt[0:10000])
xlabel('time [sec]')
ylabel('Amplitude')
title('Filtered PAM signal using "rect" pulse for \n"I failed MyTest" text')
ylim(-2,2)
grid()
In [9]:
sf.showeye(bt,Fs,FB,NTd = 100, dispparms=[0.5,3,-2,2])

Analysis of eye diagrams of signal and the filtered signal: It can be observed that there is no ISI at t=nTB in both the signals. But, there is ISI at t!=nTB in matched filtered signal b(t) as we can see in its eye diagram. The eye gets closed by approximately 50% because of ISI (at time instances other than nTB) in b(t).
